<http://nyc.gov/html/doh/html/public/press00/pr110104.html>

A Fourteenth Case of West Nile Virus Infection Reported in New York City
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
On Wed 4 Oct 2000, the New York City Health Commissioner Neal L. Cohen,
M.D., announced that a 37 year-old Staten Island man has tested positive
for West Nile virus (WNV). This individual, who lives in Bulls Head, Staten
Island, was admitted to the hospital on 27 Sep 2000 with encephalitis,
after having experienced symptoms including headache, muscle weakness, and
joint pain for several weeks. He was released from the hospital on 1 Oct
2000, and is at home recovering. The laboratory results were obtained by
tests performed at the New York City Department of Health's (NYCDOH)
laboratories, and specimens have been sent to the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention (CDC) for further confirmation.
A total of 14 people have been diagnosed with West Nile virus in New York
City in 2000, 10 of whom are residents of Staten Island. Three others are
residents of Brooklyn and one is a Queens resident. [N.B. One of the
Brooklyn residents has dual residency in New Jersey and is listed also by
the New Jersey authorities in their totals -Mod. Twelve of those diagnosed
with West Nile virus are recovering at home while 2 Brooklyn residents
remain in the hospital, including an 87 year-old Borough Park woman who
remains in a coma.
The following is a Summary of West Nile virus Findings as of 4 Oct 2000: 14
humans, 145 birds, and 146 mosquito pools. The breakdown by Boroughs is as
follows: Staten Island - Birds, 55; Mosquito Pools, 11; Humans, 10;
Manhattan - Birds, 29; Mosquito Pools, 16: Queens - Birds, 24; Mosquito
Pools, 5; Humans, 1: Bronx - Birds, 10; Mosquito Pools, 6: Brooklyn -
Birds, 27; Mosquito Pools, 8; Humans, 2 (both hospitalized). In addition,
one of the 14 persons spends time in Brooklyn and New Jersey. Extensive
information is also included on he City's Website at .
